MY WORK

Smart Doorbell Project

As part of my final year project at university, I chose to conduct a study on IoT security within smart homes. This involved me creating a smart doorbell that utilised common communication protocols such as SMTP and MQTT to secure communication between the doorbell and the hosts receiving notification of it being rang. by doing so, I was then able to carry out security tests to demonstrate how effective these protocols are at protecting our data as we use smart devices more in our daily lives. The paper written alongside this project allowed me to also highlight the dangers faced by a smart network not properly configured with the correct security measures in place. For more info check out the button above.

Python Port Scanner

In the ever-evolving landscape of cybersecurity, understanding the vulnerabilities and open ports on a network is paramount. This network port scanner project was conceived and developed as a powerful tool to aid network administrators, security professionals, and ethical hackers in their mission to secure digital assets. The primary goals of the network port scanner project were as follows:

Efficiency:
Create a fast and reliable tool capable of scanning a wide range of network hosts and ports in minimal time.
Easy to Use:
Create a user-friendly interface so anyone can use it, regardless of device capabilities.
Accuracy:
Ensure it correctly finds open ports without making mistakes.
Customisation:
Allow users to adjust the scanning to their needs.

These were the technologies used within this project:

Python:
The tool was made using Python, which is good for this kind of work.
Socket Programming:
This is how it talks to other computers on the network.
Multi-Threading:
So it can handle multiple scans at once, which makes it faster.
Command Line User Interface:
It has a simple text-based interface you can use.

This project helps people make their networks safer by finding and fixing weak points. It's a useful tool for network experts and anyone who wants to keep their data secure. To see the full code, feel free to check out the button above.

Java Load Balancer

The Load Balancer Program is a software tool designed to optimise the performance and reliability of websites and web applications. It distributes incoming network traffic across multiple servers, ensuring that no single server becomes overloaded, thus enhancing the overall speed and reliability of the services/processes it balances. The primary objectives of this project were as follows:

Efficiency:
Create a load balancing system that intelligently distributes incoming traffic, preventing server overload and improving response times.
High Availability:
Ensure that the system can detect server failures and automatically redirect traffic to healthy servers to minimise downtime.
Scalability:
Develop a solution that can easily accommodate for an increasing number of servers to handle growing workloads.

These are the technologies used within this project:

Java:
The program was written in Java because it was most suitable for this kind of work.
Balancing Rules:
Different ways of deciding how to share the workload, round robin algorithm was used to check how busy each server was before distributing work.
Checking Status:
Methods to verify that a computer/server is okay by sending a message and waiting for a reply.
Easy Changes:
Being able to easily add or remove computers without stopping the program.

This program helps websites and apps stay fast and reliable, even when lots of people are using them. This is a handy tool for anyone who runs websites or web apps, by allowing them to run at their best. For more information on the code behind this project check out the button above.

Network Testing Project

The Network Testing Project with Kali Linux and OpenVAS was a cybersecurity initiative aimed at demonstrating the process behind evaluating the security of computer network. By simulating real-world attacks and vulnerabilities, this same method can be used to help organisations identify and rectify weaknesses in their network infrastructure. This project was undertaken with several key objectives in mind:

Security Assessment:
Conduct comprehensive security assessments to identify vulnerabilities and weaknesses in target networks.
Risk mitigation:
Provide actionable insights and recommendations to enhance network security and minimise potential threats.
Real-World Simulation:
Simulate real-world cyberattacks to gauge network resilience and preparedness.
Knowledge Sharing via reports:
Share findings and best practices with network administrators to empower them in safeguarding their networks.

These are the technologies that were used within this project:

Kali Linux:
The project primarily relied on Kali Linux, a versatile cybersecurity platform used for conducting network assessments.
OpenVAS:
OpenVAS (Vulnerability Assessment System) was employed for vulnerability scanning and assessment, to identify weaknesses in the targeted network.
Metasploit:
Metasploit is a widely-used testing framework and was used to simulate cyberattacks and gauge network defences.
Networking Tools:
Various networking tools within Kali Linux were utilised to gather information and conduct tests.

This project with Kali Linux and OpenVAS can help organisations proactively identify and mitigate vulnerabilities in their network infrastructure. By simulating cyberattacks and providing actionable recommendations, it empowers network administrators to bolster their defences and protect sensitive data. This project represents my commitment to enhancing network security using these methods and addressing security weaknesses before they can be exploited by malicious actors.

Embedded Systems Arduino Uno

The Embedded Systems Traffic Light Control project with Arduino Uno is a practical demonstration of how embedded systems can be used to manage traffic flow at intersections. By leveraging the Arduino Uno platform, this project simulates a traffic light system to regulate vehicle and pedestrian traffic efficiently and safely. This project aimed to achieve the following objectives:

Traffic Management:
Create a functional traffic light system to control the flow of vehicles and pedestrians at an intersection.
Realistic Simulation:
Design the system to mimic real-world traffic light behaviour with accurate timing and sequencing.
Educational Resource:
Serve as an educational tool to help myself and others understand the principles of embedded systems and traffic management.

These are the technologies that were used within this project:

Arduino Uno:
The project is built around the Arduino Uno microcontroller board.
Embedded Programming:
C/C++ programming is used to create the embedded system logic.
LEDs:
Light-emitting diodes (LEDs) are employed to represent traffic light signals.
Sensors:
Sensors or buttons can be used to interact with the traffic light system.

The Embedded Systems Traffic Light Control project serves as an excellent educational resource for understanding embedded systems, programming, and traffic control principles.

Web Design - For UoN Societies

The Web Design project for UoN's Negotiation Society was a creative endeavour aimed at enhancing the online presence and functionality of the society's digital platform. By designing and developing a visually appealing and user-friendly website, this project helped the Negotiation Society effectively engage with its members, share information, and promote its activities. This web design project was driven by several key objectives:

Enhanced Online Presence:
Create a modern, professional, and visually appealing website that reflects the society's identity and values.
User-Centric Design:
Prioritize user experience by making the website easy to navigate, informative, and engaging for both members and potential participants.
Information Dissemination:
Provide a central hub for sharing society news, event details, resources, and negotiation-related content.
Membership Engagement:
Facilitate member interaction through forums, newsletters, and event registration features.

These are the technologies that were used within this project:

Web Design Tools:
Popular web design and development tools and languages, such as HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, were used to create the website.
Content Management System (CMS):
A CMS like WordPress or Drupal may have been employed for easy content management.
Responsive Design:
Techniques for responsive web design ensured the website's compatibility with various devices.
Web Hosting:
Hosting services were used to make the website accessible online.

The Web Design project for UoN's Negotiation Society as my first client significantly enhanced the society's online presence and strengthened its communication with it's members and the broader community. The website serves as a hub for information sharing, member engagement, and event promotion.
